        "name": "",
        "username": "RRRSU",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/f9ae1b/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2025-01-05T22:51:31.626Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Apologies if I am hijacking this thread, in which case I don’t mind to create a new thread but as this is related I thought it might help other users to have everything in one place.</p>\n<p>I have had Signal for a while, but due to damaging my iPhone 7 (screen broken) and not repairing it for a while (6-12months?), I have only just repaired it and would like to migrate the Signal from this iPhone (7) to a new iPhone. My plan was to use the iOS-to-iOS transfer feature built into the Signal app. I do not want to lose my chat history.</p>\n<p>Some challenges:<br>\n-Currently installed app version is 6.x whereas the latest Signal version in App Store is 7.x. A message appears at the top of my Signal home page (where the list of chats appear) saying this version is no longer supported and that I need to upgrade<br>\n-iOS is also 1 version behind (14.x whereas latest supported version for this model is 15.x). So I probably need to update to 15 before I can update Signal to the latest version.<br>\n-Main challenge: Due to non-use it seems my Signal account has been disabled/deleted (not sure if there’s a difference). I have confirmed this by asking a friend to try and message me, and the message fails to send and appears with a red ! and says “Contact is not a Signal User” when tapped</p>\n<p>Due to my Signal account now being inactive, I am hesitant to do anything in case it wipes out all my chat history. Some questions I have:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>How do I activate my Signal account again? (I do know the Signal PIN if that is relevant, and I still have the same mobile number)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Will this process wipe out my chat history? Presumably I would need to update the app before I could do this?</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>If I update the Signal app in the App Store to the latest version, will Signal check that I have a registered/active account and if it detects that I don’t, then wipe my current chat history?</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>It’s also worth noting that during the time that the phone was damaged, the phone was still on, but only with Mobile Data enabled, not WiFi, and Mobile Data with Signal was disabled in iPhone Settings. (The phone was partially usable during this time but part of the screen was unusable). There may have been the odd occasion where WiFi was inadvertently switched on and temporarily connected to a WiFi network.</p>",
